Full.Text: President Biden spoke today with Amir Sheikh Tamim Bin Hamad Al-Thani of Qatar. The two leaders discussed the urgent need for all hostages held by Hamas to be released without further delay.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: The leaders also discussed ongoing efforts to increase the flow of urgently needed humanitarian assistance into Gaza and Israel’s decision to resume fuel deliveries for life-saving aid. The leaders agreed to remain in close touch, including through their teams, on these matters.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: The U.S. is working closely with Israel and our partners in the region to ensure the continued delivery of fuel so lifesaving humanitarian aid can be delivered and essential services in Gaza can be restored.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: We are glad Israel agreed to fuel deliveries to Gaza at our strong request. We believe these deliveries should continue on a regular basis and in larger quantities.

Full.Text: @WhiteHouse The Biden-Harris Administration will keep fighting to lower prescription drug costs and give folks more breathing room.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Dawn’s story is one that too many Americans can unfortunately relate to. In 2022, seniors spent over $238 million out-of-pocket on Januvia – all while Big Pharma made record profits.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Under President Biden, Medicare now has the ability to negotiate lower prescription drug prices for seniors under the Inflation Reduction Act, and Januvia is one of the first ten drugs selected for this program.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Dawn’s co-pays on her lifesaving medications used to be $100, but have skyrocketed to $350 to $400 a month. Now, she and her husband David often are forced to decide which bill to pay late each month in order to afford her prescriptions and make ends meet.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: In 2001, Dawn worked for the Mayor’s Office in New York City, just two blocks away from the Twin Towers. She fell ill afterwards, and relies on 10 to 15 medicines to keep her alive – including Januvia.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Meet Dawn. She’s one of the many Americans who rely on Januvia to stay alive – and thanks to President Biden’s Inflation Reduction Act, she could soon benefit from lower out-of-pocket prescription drug costs on her medication. https://t.co/Tb5PVnRENV

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: And Judy isn’t alone. Seniors across the country paid over $43 million out-of-pocket on Enbrel in 2022, all while Big Pharma made record profits. It’s outrageous – and President Biden is doing something about it.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Judy and her husband have to watch their wallets a little closer and plan ahead for any big or major expenses so they can afford to pay $339 out-of-pocket per month for Enbrel.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: For over 40 years, Judy has been living with psoriatic arthritis and psoriasis. Since 2007, she has been taking Enbrel to help treat her conditions. Like so many other Americans, Judy struggles to afford the cost of the medicine she needs to survive.

Author: WhiteHouse

Full.Text: And, Don has inspired his mom and multiple other friends to get over-the-counter hearing aids as well, helping to improve their quality of life. This Administration will continue to work to lower costs for families.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Don went and got a pair of hearing aids for the first time. His insurance didn’t cover the cost, but over-the-counter hearing aids were half the cost of prescription ones – up to thousands of dollars cheaper – so he purchased a pair.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Around the time Don began to look into hearing aids, the Biden-Harris Administration accelerated making hearing aids available over-the-counter as part of President Biden’s Competition Agenda.

Author: WhiteHouse
Full.Text: Since then, things have improved for Don immensely. He can now fully engage in conversations with his family and friends around the dinner table without having to ask people to repeat themselves. He no longer has to turn the TV volume up to levels his children find annoying.

Author: WhiteHouse

Full.Text: It was a relief to leave. Problems with the room included: Tired fixtures and fittings Broken or damaged furniture Uncomfortable beds with springs sticking through the mattress Mysterious brown stain on the wall Dirty kettle Ripped/fraying curtains Rotting wooden window frames (unpainted) Stained bathroom tiles Slow draining shower Rusty fittings in the bathroom Dodgy switch in the bathroom 2 dead plug sockets in the room Couldn’t close the window Chest of drawers didn’t close TV did not switch on. Problems with the hotel: Really noisy from the corridor (particularly at night and early in the morning) The staircases up to room were really narrow and steep and too small to put your foot down safely. I really struggled to take my case up and down and nearly fell. Lift had broken on arrival. Rooms had not been cleaned and were not ready on arrival. Stairs up to reception are really narrow and uneven and difficult and dangerous to carry a case up and down. Entry way to secondary building (with lift) in a poor state of repair. My other concern was the company’s policy of taking money from my account without warning. I was told that I would pay the whole balance for the room on check-in and yet this was debited from my account a week before without even so much as an email to warn me. £88, (which I later found out was the security deposit) was also debited from my account 3 days before check-in, when the terms and conditions set out by Booking.com once again specified that this would be taken at check-in. At check-in, I was then debited a further £7 and none of the reception staff could tell me what this was for, it was just ‘on the system’. Staff were also unhelpful when it came to complaints and communication was poor. My colleagues who were staying in another room at the hotel and had paid more and left after the first night and moved to another hotel.
